Dose Response - Example Custom Code

Renuka R. Nayak

8/20/2020

1 Introduction

This R markdown document provides code used in the analysis of 16S-seq data from gnotobiotic mice humanized with stool from a heathy donor and then subsequently treated with either PBS, low dose or high dose methotrexate (MTX). The results of this experiment as well as other similar experiments are from our manuscript:

Nayak et al, Methotrexate impacts conserved pathways in diverse human gut bacteria leading to decreased host immune activation. In revision.

2 Experimental Design

From our mansucript:

We colonized germ-free mice with a stool sample collected from a healthy human male (Donor 1; Tables S1A and S1B) prior to the oral administration of vehicle, low-dose MTX (1 mg/kg), or high-dose MTX (50 mg/kg), selected to span doses used to treat arthritis (Koyama et al., 2017) and cancer (Chabner and Young, 1973) in murine models (see Methods). Daily stool samples and endpoint samples from the cecum and colon were analyzed using 16S rRNA gene sequencing (16S-seq; Tables S2A and S2B) and quantitative PCR (qPCR), and daily weights were assessed (Table S3A).

2.1 Analysis Notes

Some of the code in this document has been adapted from: https://f1000researchdata.s3.amazonaws.com/manuscripts/10545/387d9a79-c4ab-4676-8466-583e3fb2c85f_8986_-_susan_holmes_v2.pdf?doi=10.12688/f1000research.8986.2

2.2 Manuscript Results

The code in this Rmd was used to support the following paragraph from the Results of our manuscript:

Total colonization (Figure 1A) and microbial richness (Figure 1B) were comparable between group. MTX significantly altered gut microbial community structure after 1 day (ANOSIM, R=0.60, p=0.006) and this effect persisted to the final day of treatment (ANOSIM, R=0.75, p=0.006) (Figure 1C). There was no significant difference between groups prior to treatment (ANOSIM, R=0.23 p=0.109). High-dose MTX significantly decreased the Bacteroidetes phylum compared to vehicle controls (Day 4 DESeq padj=0.001, Figure 1D). Analyses of longitudinal trends with a generalized linear mixed-effects model, confirmed that Bacteroidetes were decreased (slope=-0.066, p=0.007). No other phyla were significantly altered using either analysis. High-dose MTX altered 14 bacterial genera and 81 amplicon sequence variants (ASVs) spanning multiple phyla including Actinobacteria, Firmicutes, and Proteobacteria (Figure 1E; Table S2C). Low-dose MTX had a more modest effect that was significant when taking into account longitudinal trends [PERMANOVA: R2=0.22, p=0.001, low-dose; R2=0.38, p=0.001, high-dose]. Low-dose MTX significantly altered 26 ASVs (Figure 1E; Table S2C), including 19 that were also altered in a consistent direction in the high-dose group (Figure 1F). Endpoint samples from the cecum and colon revealed significant differences in community structure (Figures 1G and 1H) and ASVs (Table S2C) that were comparable to stool samples (Figure 1I).

4.2 Transform Data

Create transformed versions of the data to perform subsequent analyses.

#Convenience functions for geometric mean and clr transform
gm_mean = function(x, na.rm=TRUE){
  # The geometric mean, with some error-protection bits.
  exp(sum(log(x[x > 0 & !is.na(x)]), na.rm=na.rm) / length(x))
  }

#holmes method
clr1 = function(x, base=2){
  x <- log((x / gm_mean(x)), base)
  x[!is.finite(x) | is.na(x)] <- 0.0
  return(x)
  }

#alternative clr method - adding a pseudocount of 1 to values that are 0
clr2 = function(x, base=2){
  x <- log((x / gm_mean(x)), base)
  x[!is.finite(x) | is.na(x)] <- log((1 / gm_mean(x)), base)
  return(x)
}

#set clr function to see if this affects overall results.
clr=clr1

#clr transform data for PCA, multivariate analysis, visualization
ps_clr <- transform_sample_counts(ps0, clr )

#proportion data for visualization
ps_prop <- transform_sample_counts(ps0, function (x) x/sum(x))

#rarefied data for ANOSIM and PERMANOVA
set.seed(25123)
ps_rarefied <- rarefy_even_depth(ps0, sample.size=min(sample_sums(ps0)))

Composition is different at day 4 based on MTX dose, but not pre-treatment.

4.7 DESeq2 Analysis

Determine which taxa are differentially abundant at the ASV, genus, and phylum levels.

We referenced the following: https://www.bioconductor.org/packages/devel/bioc/vignettes/phyloseq/inst/doc/phyloseq-mixture-models.html

4.7.1 ASV Level

library(DESeq2)
alpha = 0.01 #SET significance threshold
set.seed(10)

#LOW DOSE COMPARISON
ps_deseq <- ps0
ps_deseq=subset_samples(ps_deseq, 
                        MethotrexateDose %in% c("0 mg/kg","1 mg/kg") & TimePoint %in% c(4)) 
deseq_mtx=phyloseq_to_deseq2(ps_deseq, ~ MethotrexateDose)
geoMeans = apply(counts(deseq_mtx), 1, gm_mean)
deseq_mtx = estimateSizeFactors(deseq_mtx, geoMeans = geoMeans)
deseq_mtx = DESeq(deseq_mtx, test="Wald", fitType="parametric")
res = results(deseq_mtx, cooksCutoff = FALSE)
res2 = cbind(as(res, "data.frame"), as(tax_table(ps_deseq)[rownames(res), ], "matrix"))
sigtab = res[which(res$padj < alpha), ]  #SET significance threshold above
sigtab = cbind(as(sigtab, "data.frame"), as(tax_table(ps_deseq)[rownames(sigtab), ], "matrix"))
dim(sigtab)
## [1] 26 14
print(paste("There are", dim(sigtab)[1],"differentially abundant ASVs with low dose MTX treatment."))
## [1] "There are 26 differentially abundant ASVs with low dose MTX treatment."
sigtab_low <- sigtab
sigtab_low_day4_rsv <- sigtab_low

#HIGH DOSE COMPARISON
ps_deseq <- ps0
ps_deseq=subset_samples(ps_deseq, 
                        MethotrexateDose %in% c("0 mg/kg","50 mg/kg") & TimePoint %in% c(4)) 
deseq_mtx=phyloseq_to_deseq2(ps_deseq, ~ MethotrexateDose)
geoMeans = apply(counts(deseq_mtx), 1, gm_mean)
deseq_mtx = estimateSizeFactors(deseq_mtx, geoMeans = geoMeans)

res2 = cbind(as(res, "data.frame"), as(tax_table(ps_deseq)[rownames(res), ], "matrix"))
sigtab = res[which(res$padj < alpha), ] #SET significance threshold above
sigtab = cbind(as(sigtab, "data.frame"), as(tax_table(ps_deseq)[rownames(sigtab), ], "matrix"))

4.7.2 Genus Level

The code below looks at genera instead of ASVs.

#AGGLOMERATE OVER GENUS to perform DeSeq
#Run only on Day 4 samples

alpha = 0.01 #SET significance threshold

#LOW DOSE COMPARISON
ps_deseq <- tax_glom(ps0, "Genus", NArm = TRUE)

                        MethotrexateDose %in% c("0 mg/kg","1 mg/kg") & TimePoint %in% c(4))

geoMeans = apply(counts(deseq_mtx), 1, gm_mean)

sigtab = res[which(res$padj < alpha), ]  #SET significance threshold above
if (dim(sigtab)[1] > 0){
  sigtab = cbind(as(sigtab, "data.frame"), as(tax_table(ps_deseq)[rownames(sigtab), ], "matrix"))
}

4.8 GLMM Analysis

Adapted from: https://github.com/slyalina/Mouse_IBD_2017_paper_supporting_code/blob/master/GLMM_code.Rmd

###Set Up Function

library(cplm)
library(lazyeval)
library(doParallel)
library(R.utils)
library(DT)

glmm_time_trend = function(data, # input dataframe
                           hierarchy1_col, # column name for gene level grouping (ex: "KO")
                           hierarchy2_col = NULL, # column name for pathway level grouping; optional (ex: "module_id")
                           #NOTE: if hierarchy2_col is empty then testing happens on per-gene groups
                           response_col, # column name holding the response variable (ex: "Abundance")
                           time_col, # column name holding numeric time values (ex: "week") 
                           group_col, # column name holding factor separating data into groups to be contrasted (ex: "group")
                           cases_label, # value of the group column that correponds to "cases" (ex: "DNR")
                           individual_col, # column name that specifies subjects
                           levels_to_test = NULL, # smaller set of values to test than all levels of ontological grouping
                           extra_covars=c(), # any additonal variables affecting response; optional (ex: "kit")
                           time_out=300, # constrain the time alloted for fitting each model (in seconds)
                           log_file = "") # write intermediate results to log for monitoring, otherwise print to stdout
{

    if(is.null(levels_to_test)){
        if(is.null(hierarchy2_col)){
            levels_to_test = unique(unlist(data[,hierarchy1_col]))
        }
        else{
            levels_to_test = unique(unlist(data[,hierarchy2_col]))
        }
    }
    write(paste(c("name","p_intercept","p_slope","coeff_intercept","coeff_slope"),collapse = " "),file = log_file,append = TRUE)
    glmm_results = foreach(lvl = levels_to_test,
                           .inorder = TRUE,
                           .packages = c("cplm","dplyr","lazyeval","R.utils")
                            ) %dopar% {
        tryCatch({
            # Subset the data to either all the genes in pathway being looekd at,
            # or just the one gene if not doing higher level grouping
            data_here = data %>%
                filter_(interp(~lvl_tested == lvl,
                               lvl_tested = as.name(ifelse(!is.null(hierarchy2_col),
                                                           hierarchy2_col,
                                                           hierarchy1_col))))
            # Assemble model formulas from provided variable names to fit 3 models
            fmla0 = sprintf("%s ~ %s %s %s + (1 + %s | %s) %s",
                            response_col,
                            time_col,
                            ifelse(length(extra_covars) > 0,"+",""),
                            paste(extra_covars,collapse = " + "),
                            time_col,
                            individual_col,
                            ifelse(!is.null(hierarchy2_col),
                                sprintf("+ (1 + %s|%s)",time_col,hierarchy1_col),
                                ""
                            ))
            fmla1 = sprintf("%s ~ %s + %s %s %s + (1 + %s | %s) %s",
                            response_col,
                            time_col,
                            group_col,
                            ifelse(length(extra_covars) > 0,"+",""),
                            paste(extra_covars,collapse = " + "),
                            time_col,
                            individual_col,
                            ifelse(!is.null(hierarchy2_col),
                                sprintf("+ (1 + %s|%s)",time_col,hierarchy1_col),
                                ""
                            ))
            fmla2 = sprintf("%s ~ %s * %s %s %s + (1 + %s | %s) %s",
                            response_col,
                            time_col,
                            group_col,
                            ifelse(length(extra_covars) > 0,"+",""),
                            paste(extra_covars,collapse = " + "),
                            time_col,
                            individual_col,
                            ifelse(!is.null(hierarchy2_col),
                                sprintf("+ (1 + %s|%s)",time_col,hierarchy1_col),
                                ""
                            ))
            fit0 = withTimeout(do.call("cpglmm",list(formula=formula(fmla0),
                                                         data=as.name("data_here"),
                                                         control=list(max.iter=3000,
                                                                      max.fun=20000))),
                                   timeout = time_out,onTimeout = "error")
            fit1 = withTimeout(do.call("cpglmm",list(formula=formula(fmla1),
                                                         data=as.name("data_here"),
                                                         control=list(max.iter=3000,
                                                                      max.fun=20000))),
                                   timeout = time_out,onTimeout = "error")
            fit2 = withTimeout(do.call("cpglmm",list(formula=formula(fmla2),
                                                         data=as.name("data_here"),
                                                         control=list(max.iter=3000,
                                                                      max.fun=20000))),
                                   timeout = time_out,onTimeout = "error")
            anova_res = anova(fit0,fit1,fit2) # does LRT on the set of nested models
            p_vals = anova_res$`Pr(>Chisq)`[2:3]
            coeffs = cplm::fixef(fit2) # take estimates from most complex model
            write(sprintf("%s   %G  %G  %f  %f",lvl,
                          p_vals[1],
                          p_vals[2],
                          coeffs[paste0(group_col,cases_label)],
                          coeffs[paste0(time_col,":",group_col,cases_label)]),
                  file = log_file,append = TRUE)
            return(list(p_interaction = p_vals[2],
                        p_intercept = p_vals[1],
                        coeff_interaction = coeffs[paste0(time_col,":",group_col,cases_label)],
                        coeff_intercept = coeffs[paste0(group_col,cases_label)],
                        fit = list(aov=anova_res,
                                   index=fit2@p,
                                   disp=fit2@phi,
                                   coefs=coeffs)))}
            ,error = function(e) { #If an error ocurred or model fitting timed out return a list of NAs
                write(toString(e), file=log_file, append = TRUE)
                return(list(NA,NA,NA,NA,NA))
            }
        )
}
    names(glmm_results) = levels_to_test
    return(glmm_results)
}

7 Example Code Comments

This code provides an example of how the initial gnotobiotic experiment in which mice were treated with 2 doses of MTX were analyzed. Experiments in which mice were individually housed (Figure S1) as well as the route and rescue experiments (Figure S2) were analyzed in similar ways.

7.1 Combined Analysis

For the combined analysis presented in Figure S3, we combined phyloseq objects form the different gnotobiotic experiments in which mice were treated with high dose MTX. We included a variable for experiment or donor as well to determine the impacts of each of these variables and their contributions to community composition.

An example of the DESeq formula used this analysis is:

deseq_mtx=phyloseq_to_deseq2(ps_deseq, ~ exp+MTXcontrast) geoMeans = apply(counts(deseq_mtx), 1, gm_mean) deseq_mtx = estimateSizeFactors(deseq_mtx, geoMeans = geoMeans) deseq_mtx = DESeq(deseq_mtx, test="Wald", fitType="parametric")
